          <section id="crop-management" class="section active">
    <h2>Crop Management Tips</h2>
    <p>Best practices for planting, watering, and harvesting include:</p>
    <div class="card-container">
        <!-- Card 1: Understanding Local Climate -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Understanding Local Climate:</strong> 
                    Select crop varieties that can thrive in your region's temperature and weather conditions. For example, warm-season crops like tomatoes and peppers need hot summers, while cool-season crops like spinach and lettuce prefer milder climates.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/sites/g/files/anmtlf171/files/sites/default/files/infographic-observing-earths-global-climate.png" alt="Local Climate" />
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Card 2: Soil Conditions -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Soil Conditions:</strong> 
                    Different crops need different soil types. Acidic soils suit crops like potatoes, while neutral or alkaline soils work best for beans. Choose varieties that suit your soil's pH, texture, and fertility.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/3-s2.0-B9780323853439000240-f22-01-9780323853439.jpg" alt="Soil Conditions" />
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Card 3: Disease and Pest Resistance -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Disease and Pest Resistance:</strong> 
                    Choose varieties that are resistant to common pests and diseases in your area. For example, certain tomato varieties resist blight, while others are better suited to repel insects.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://news.ucsb.edu/sites/default/files/images/2022/Pesticides.jpg" alt="Pest Resistance" />
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Card 4: Crop Maturity Time -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Crop Maturity Time:</strong> 
                    For regions with shorter growing seasons, opt for faster-maturing crop varieties. This ensures that crops are harvested before unfavorable weather conditions such as frost.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/289451676/figure/fig2/AS:667788242849815@1536224532909/Phenological-stages-of-wheat-crop.png" alt="Maturity Time" />
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Card 5: Yield and Quality Preferences -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Yield and Quality Preferences:</strong> 
                    Consider your market needs. High-yield varieties may be productive but might not meet market quality standards. Choose varieties known for the quality and type of produce suited to your customers.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/360662874/figure/fig1/AS:1157085798641669@1652882160054/Real-time-crop-selection-features.jpg" alt="Quality Preferences" />
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

            <section id="pest-control" class="section">
    <h2>Pest Control</h2>
    <p>Effective pest management is crucial to ensure healthy crop growth. Here are some key guidelines to manage pests and diseases:</p>
    <div class="card-container">
        
        <!-- Card 1: Identify Pests Before Applying Treatments -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Identify Pests Before Applying Treatments:</strong> 
                    Proper identification is the first step in pest management. Different pests require different treatments, and misidentification can lead to wasted efforts and damage to crops. 
                    Observing insect types, damage patterns on leaves or stems, and consulting local pest control guides can help.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/329263432/figure/fig1/AS:698144681652229@1543462071355/Sample-images-of-24-insect-species-collected-from-crop-fields.jpg" alt="Pest Identification" />
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Card 2: Use Natural Predators -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Use Natural Predators Whenever Possible:</strong> 
                    Beneficial insects, such as ladybugs and lacewings, feed on harmful pests like aphids and caterpillars. Introducing or encouraging these natural predators reduces the need for chemical pesticides and promotes a balanced ecosystem.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/natural-predators.jpg" alt="Natural Predators" />
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Card 3: Implement Crop Rotation -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Implement Crop Rotation to Disrupt Pest Cycles:</strong> 
                    Crop rotation breaks the life cycle of many pests by changing the host plant year after year. For example, rotating corn and beans can help prevent pests like rootworms, which thrive when the same crop is planted in the same field repeatedly.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/crop-rotation.jpg" alt="Crop Rotation" />
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Card 4: Maintain Cleanliness and Sanitation -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Maintain Cleanliness and Sanitation:</strong> 
                    Removing debris and cleaning up fallen leaves or plants prevents pests from finding places to hide and breed. This practice helps reduce the chances of a pest outbreak and keeps crops healthy.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/cleanliness.jpg" alt="Sanitation in Fields" />
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Card 5: Use Organic Pesticides -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Use Organic Pesticides When Necessary:</strong> 
                    When natural methods are insufficient, organic pesticides such as neem oil, insecticidal soaps, or biological agents can help manage pest populations without harming the environment or beneficial insects.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/organic-pesticides.jpg" alt="Organic Pesticides" />
            </div>
        </div>

    </div>
</section>


            <section id="soil-health" class="section">
    <h2>Soil Health</h2>
    <p>Maintaining healthy soil is essential for productive farming. Here are some key practices for improving soil health:</p>
    <div class="card-container">
        
        <!-- Card 1: Conduct Soil Tests -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Conduct Soil Tests to Understand Nutrient Levels:</strong> 
                    Soil testing provides valuable insights into nutrient levels and pH balance. Regular testing helps farmers understand their soil's needs, enabling them to apply appropriate fertilizers and amendments for optimal crop growth.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/soil-testing.jpg" alt="Soil Testing" />
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Card 2: Add Organic Matter -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Add Organic Matter to Improve Soil Structure:</strong> 
                    Adding organic matter such as compost, manure, or cover crops enhances soil fertility, structure, and water retention. This practice also encourages beneficial microbial activity, which is vital for healthy plant growth.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/organic-matter.jpg" alt="Adding Organic Matter" />
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Card 3: Practice Cover Cropping -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Practice Cover Cropping to Prevent Erosion:</strong> 
                    Cover crops, such as clover and rye, are planted during the off-season to protect the soil from erosion and nutrient depletion. These crops help hold the soil in place, improve soil health, and add nutrients back into the soil when turned under.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/cover-cropping.jpg" alt="Cover Cropping" />
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Card 4: Utilize Crop Rotation -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Utilize Crop Rotation to Enhance Soil Fertility:</strong> 
                    Rotating different crops each season improves soil fertility by breaking pest and disease cycles and allowing soil nutrients to replenish. Different plants have varying nutrient needs, so rotating them can maintain a balanced soil ecosystem.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/crop-rotation.jpg" alt="Crop Rotation" />
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Card 5: Practice No-Till Farming -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Practice No-Till Farming:</strong> 
                    No-till farming reduces soil disturbance, maintaining soil structure and moisture. This method helps prevent erosion and enhances the soil's ability to store carbon, contributing to overall soil health and reducing the need for chemical fertilizers.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/no-till-farming.jpg" alt="No-Till Farming" />
            </div>
        </div>

    </div>
</section>


         <section id="climate-advice" class="section">
    <h2>Climate Advice</h2>
    <p>Understanding local climate conditions is crucial for successful farming. Here are some suggested practices to adapt to varying climate challenges:</p>
    <div class="card-container">
        
        <!-- Card 1: Adjust Planting Dates -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Adjust Planting Dates Based on Seasonal Weather Patterns:</strong> 
                    Monitoring seasonal weather patterns is vital for determining the optimal planting dates. Early planting can lead to crop failure due to frost, while late planting may not allow crops enough time to mature. Adapt your planting schedule to local climate trends to maximize yields.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/planting-dates.jpg" alt="Adjust Planting Dates" />
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Card 2: Utilize Shade or Windbreaks -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Utilize Shade or Windbreaks to Protect Crops:</strong> 
                    Planting trees or shrubs as windbreaks can reduce wind damage and protect crops from harsh weather conditions. Additionally, using shade cloth or planting shade trees can help reduce heat stress during hot seasons, improving crop survival and quality.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/windbreaks.jpg" alt="Windbreaks" />
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Card 3: Implement Water Conservation Techniques -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Implement Water Conservation Techniques During Dry Periods:</strong> 
                    During dry spells, employing water conservation techniques is crucial. Methods such as drip irrigation, mulching, and rainwater harvesting can help maintain soil moisture and reduce water usage while ensuring that crops receive the necessary hydration.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/water-conservation.jpg" alt="Water Conservation Techniques" />
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <!-- Card 4: Monitor Local Weather Forecasts -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Monitor Local Weather Forecasts:</strong> 
                    Staying informed about local weather forecasts can help farmers make timely decisions regarding irrigation, pest management, and crop protection. Utilize technology and apps that provide accurate weather predictions for your area.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/weather-monitoring.jpg" alt="Weather Monitoring" />
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Card 5: Adapt Crop Selection to Climate -->
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-content">
                <p><strong>Adapt Crop Selection to Climate:</strong> 
                    Choose crop varieties that are resilient to your local climate conditions. For example, drought-resistant varieties can help maintain productivity during dry spells, while heat-tolerant crops may thrive in warmer climates.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="card-image">
                <img src="https://example.com/crop-selection.jpg" alt="Crop Selection" />
            </div>
        </div>

    </div>
</section>

